## 1. Introduction

**Scope Boundary:** This TDD specifies HOW to implement the Auto-detect Runtime & Run Indexer feature. It does NOT repeat functional requirements, business rules, or use cases — refer to the FSD for those. This document focuses on: technology choices, architecture decisions, implementation patterns, and code structure.

### 1.1 Purpose

This TDD provides the technical design for implementing the runtime auto-detection and indexer execution feature in the Kiro SDLC Agents VS Code extension. It covers the internal architecture of indexer.ts, the command-building strategy, process management, and error handling patterns.

### 1.2 Scope

Technical scope covers: - src/indexer.ts module — all functions - Configuration entries in src/config.ts (INDEXER\_SCRIPTS) - Configuration contribution in package.json (kiroSdlc.preferredIndexer) - Integration with src/extension.ts (command handler) - Child process management and output streaming

### 1.3 Technology Stack

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Layer | Technology | Version |
| Language | TypeScript | 5.4+ |
| Runtime | Node.js (VS Code Extension Host) | 20+ |
| Framework | VS Code Extension API | 1.85+ |
| Process Management | Node.js child\_process | Built-in |
| Path Resolution | Node.js path | Built-in |
| Build Tool | TypeScript Compiler (tsc) | 5.4+ |
| Package Manager | npm | 10+ |

### 1.4 Design Principles

* **Single Responsibility** — each function does one thing (detect, build, execute)
* **Fail-fast with graceful degradation** — detect failures early, fall back to platform defaults
* **No external dependencies** — uses only Node.js built-ins and VS Code API
* **Platform-aware** — handles Windows/Unix differences in path separators and shell commands
* **Observable** — all operations produce visible output via Output Channel

### 1.5 Constraints

* Must work within VS Code Extension Host (no native modules)
* Cannot use spawn with streaming (VS Code exec callback pattern is simpler for this use case)
* Must handle paths with spaces (common on Windows: C:\Program Files\...)
* Timeout must be configurable in future but hardcoded to 120s for now
* No network access required (all operations are local)

